<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>



<section xml:id="lesson4_1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Exploring Measurement</title>

<sidebyside widths="65% 35%" valign="top">
    <p>
     You might be thinking that we should have been able to easily tell the 
    difference between the random gate and the H gate by performing more 
    precise measurement after an H gate. That is, instead of just checking for 
    <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>\ket{1}</m>, let's measure the probability and phase at the 
    same time! 
    </p>
    <image source="H_Explore.png" width="66%" />
  </sidebyside>

<p> To better understand the situation, let's explore measurement in your daily life. 
  Measurement consists of a <em>question</em>, <em>device</em>, and <em>method</em>.</p>

<sidebyside widths="75% 25%" valign="top">
    <p>Consider measuring the length of a table:  
    <ul>
      <li><term>Question:</term> How long is the table?</li>
      <li><term>Device:</term> A tape measure</li>
      <li><term>Method:</term> Place the tape measure along the length of the table and read the value.</li>
    </ul>
    </p>
    <image source="Measure_table.png" width="66%" />
  </sidebyside>

<p> This is a very straightforward measurement. The question is clear, the device is designed for this specific measurement, 
and the method is simple. Quantum processes are much more difficult to measure. </p>

<!--<p><insert> Let's insert a question or two here having students identify the question, device, and method for a measurement scenario.
You can grab from the zines for fun examples. </insert>
<term>Question:</term>What is the speed of the car?
<term>Device:</term> A radar gun
<term>Method:</term> Place the tape measure along the length of the table and read the value.
</p>
-->

<sidebyside widths="75% 25%" valign="top">
    <p>Now, let's consider a police officer measuring the speed of a car. 
    Use this scenario to answer the next few questions about the question, device, and method.
    </p>  
    <image source="Measure_speed.png" width="66%" />
</sidebyside>

  <exercise label="L4_1 Measurement Question">
    <title>Measurement Question</title>
    <idx>L4_1 Measurement Question</idx>
    <statement>
      <p>What is the measurement question?</p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>What is the speed of the car?</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Correct!!</p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p>How many cars pass through this intersection?</p></statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p>Is the car's registration up-to-date?</p></statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
    <hint>
      <p>What is the police officer measuring?</p> 
    </hint>
  </exercise>

  <exercise label="L4_1 Measurement Device">
    <title>Measurement Device</title>
    <idx>L4_1 Measurement Device</idx>
    <statement>
      <p>What is the measurement device?</p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>A radar gun</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Correct!!</p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p>The police officer's eyes.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p>The police officer's mouth.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
    <hint>
      <p>Which device would produce an accurate measurement of the car's speed?</p> 
    </hint>
  </exercise>

  <exercise label="L4_1 Measurement Method">
    <title>Measurement Method</title>
    <idx>L4_1 Measurement Method</idx>
    <statement>
      <p>What is the measurement method?</p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>The police officer points the radar gun at the car and reads the result.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Correct!!</p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p>The police officer observes as the car drives by and draws on prior experience to figure out the car's speed.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p>The police officer counts out loud to determine how long it takes for the car to pass from point A to point B.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
    <hint>
      <p>Which method would produce an accurate measurement of the car's speed?</p> 
    </hint>
  </exercise>

</section>

